rdships of industrialized farm life, but also the healing that time can bring, and the dignity that can emerge when farm animals are allowed to age on their own terms. Each portrait is accompanied by a brief biographical note about its subject, and the book is rounded out with essays that explore the history of animal photography, the place of beauty in activist art, and much more. Open this book to any page. Meet Teresa, a thirteen-year-old Yorkshire Pig, or Melvin, an eleven-year-old Angora Goat, or Tom, a seven-year-old Broad Breasted White Turkey. You’ll never forget them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAnimal rights. 0aAnimal sanctuarieszUnited States. 0aAnimal sanctuaries-United States. 0aDomestic animalsvPictorial works. 0aDomestic animalszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aDomestic animals-Pictorial works. 0aDomestic animals-United States-Biography. 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh  aanimals, animal portraits, paintings, art, artwork, photos, photography, photographer, farms, farm sanctuaries, elderly, old, older, portrait, aging, relationships, bonds, industrialization, hardships, healing, dignity, cows, pigs, chickens, activism, activists, goat, turkey, presentation, trust, life stories, subject context, memorable, coffee table books.1 aBaur, Gene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaur, Gene.1 aLeshko, Isa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeshko, Isa.1 aMontgomery, Sy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontgomery, Sy.1 aTucker, Anne Wilkes.1 aWilkes Tucker, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311071194340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97802